
# Container Name

 $ docker container run -d -p 8080:80 --name mysiteX nginx
 --name    â†’ Assign a custom name to the container (mysiteX) ; Has to be unique. 
    Assigns a human-readable name to the container
    Makes management easier than using container IDs
**If you don't assign an 'container name', Docker will automatically assign it for you.

You directly control the container using it's name:(otherwise you have to use container ID)
 $ docker container stop mysiteX
 $ docker container start mysiteX



**What happens when you 'create' an container:
 1. Creates the container
 2. Configures iptables / NAT rules on the host.
 3. Binds host port --> Container Port.
**Ports are immutable after creation.
**Ports are linked at compile time ( when you create container )
*If you have a already created an 'container' : You can not re-define the Ports.
  You have to remove the container and re-create/run the container using required Port

**run => create + Start. 




# Run multiple containers:
$ docker container run -d -p 8081:80 --name mysite1 nginx
$ docker container run -d -p 8082:80 --name mysite2 httpd